gomodel:SYNGO_668  a      owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Fbxl20 ubiquitinates and degrades the active zone protein Rim-1 (Fig.2-4). Fbxl20 null mutant hippocampal neurons show increased spontaneous (mEPSC) frequency but not amplitude. The increased mEPSC frequency can be rescued to wild type levels by shRNA-mediated depletion of RIM-1. In hippocampal slices from Fbxl20 null mutant mice increased mini frequency can be rescued by blocking proteasome activity. Hence Fbxl20 modulates synaptic transmission by ubiquitination and degradation of Rim-1.\n\n23/5/20176 Pim\n- Experiments:\nFig.2 Fbxl20 binds SCF complex proteins involved in ubiquitination (co-IP, mouse brain), binds ubiquitinated proteins (co-IP overexpressed Fbxl20, heterologous cells), binds RIM1 (co-IP, mouse brain), colocalizes with RIM1 in neurons (conf.IF, cultured neurons), directly interacts with RIM1 (co-IP, cell free system), and mediates ubiquitination of RIM1 protein (co-IP, western blot, cell free system).\nFig.3 Levels of RIM1 protein are increased and levels of RIM1 ubiquitination are decreased in Fbxl20 KO mice (IP + western blot, genetic transformation).\nFig.4-7 Fbxl20 KO changes synaptic ultrastructure and SV release (Ephys, genetic transformation). Experimental description: M&M: \"Primary cultured neurons from SCR-KO **mice** were prepared with P1- P3 mice\"." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-9900-4233" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" ;
        dc:date           "2017-05-23" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_668" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

